We begin by presenting the Verse calculus, \versecalc, informally.  We will give its
rewrite rules precisely in \Cref{sec:rewrite-rules}.

\versecalc{} is modelled on the lambda calculus, and indeed the lambda calculus is
a sub-language of \versecalc{}.  Just like the lambda calculus, \versecalc{} is untyped;
adding a type system is an excellent goal, but is the subject of another paper.
The syntax of \versecalc{} is given in \Cref{fig:syntax}.
It has a very conventional sub-language that is just the lambda-calculus with
some built-in operations and tuples as data constructors:
\begin{itemize}
\item \emph{Head normal forms}.
A head normal form, |hnf|, is a conventional value: a built-in constant |k| or operator |op|, a tuple, also called array, |arr (v_1,dots,v_n)|, or a lambda term |lam x e|.
For the built-in constants and operators we use only integer constants, and two representative
functions |gt| and |add|, as well as |map| as a useful array operations.
For notational convenience we allow ourselves to abbreviate such tuples to just |(v_1, dots, v_n)|.
\item \emph{Values.}
In a functional logic language an expression may evaluate to an as-yet-unknown logical variable,
so a \emph{value} |v| is either a head normal form, or a variable |x|.
\item \emph{Expressions} |e| includes values |v|, and applications |applyx v_1 v_2|.  Remembering that
  a value can be a lambda, that gives us the full lambda calculus.
  \item \emph{A program}, |p|, is a closed expression from which we extract one result using |one| (see \Cref{sec:one}).
\end{itemize}
Expressions also include two other key collections of constructs:
logical variables and unification (\Cref{sec:unify}), and choice (\Cref{sec:choice}).
The details of choice and unification, and especially their
interaction, are rather tricky, so this section will do a lot of
arm-waving.  But fear not: \Cref{sec:rewrite-rules} will make all this
precise.

\subsection{Logical variables and unification} \label{sec:unify}

The Verse calculus includes first class logical variables and unification:
you can bring a fresh logical variable into scope with |defKW|; equate two expressions with |e_1 = e_2|; and
sequence two expressions with |e_1 ; e_2| (see \Cref{fig:syntax}).
As an example, what might be written |dlet x e_1 e_2| in a conventional functional language can be written
|def x (x=e_1; e_2)| in the Verse calculus.

A program executes by solving its equations, to get values for some of the logical variables.
For example
$$
|def (x,y,z) (x=(y,3); x=(2,z); y)|
$$
is solved by unifying |x| with |(y,3)| and with |(2,z)|; that in turn unifies |(y,3)| with |(2,z)|, which
unifies |y| with |2| and |z| with |3|.  Finally |y| is returned as the result.

Unification deals with pattern matching in functions. For example:
$$
|def fst ((fst = lam pr (def (a,b) (pr = (a,b); a))); applyx fst (2,5))|
$$
This term binds |fst| to a lambda, and applies that function to |(2,5)|.
The lambda unifies its argument with |(a,b)|, where |a,b| are fresh logical
variables in the body of the lambda; and returns the first of the two, namely |a|.
Although a \versecalc{} program  is just a single expression, it is tiresome to
wrap it in a binding for every support function such as |fst|, so in this presentation
we allow ourselves a set of top-level bindings for such functions.
\lennart{Use |:=| for top level functions?}

The input to |fst| may include logical variables. For example:
$$
|def (x,y,z) (x=(y,z); applyx fst x = 2; y)|
$$
Here |applyx fst x| evaluates to |y|, which we then unify with |2|; the logical
variable |z| never gets a value, but that does not matter.
Another way to say this is that, as usual in logic programming, we may
constraint the \emph{output} of a function (here |applyx fst x = 2|), and thereby
affect its \emph{input} (here |(y,z)|).

Although ``|;|'' is called ``sequencing'', the order of that sequence
is immaterial for equations.
For example\footnote{We informally write |3+y| rather than
  |applyx add (3,y)|, and similarly with other operators.},
consider |def x (x = 3+y; y = 7; x)|.  In \versecalc{} we can only unify |x| with a \emph{value};
we will see why in \Cref{sec:call-time-choice}. So the equation |x=3+y| is stuck.
No matter!  We simply leave it and try some other equation. In this case, we can make progress with |y=7|;
and that in turn unlocks |x = 3+y| because now we know that |y| is |7|, so we can evaluate |3+7| to |10|
and unify |x| with that.  The idea of leaving stuck expressions aside, and executing other parts of the
program is called \emph{residuation} \cite{hanus:survey}, and is at the heart of our mantra ``just solve the equations''.

\simon{Why are applications |applyx v1 v2| not |applyx e1 e2|?}

\subsection{Choice} \label{sec:choice} \label{sec:call-time-choice}

In conventional functional programming, an expression evaluates to a single value.
In contrast, a \versecalc{} expression (unless it gets stuck) evaluates to a choice of zero, one, or many values.
The expression |fail| yields no values; a head normal form |hnf| yields one value;
and the choice |e_1 choice e_2| yields all the values
yielded by |e_1| and all the values yielded by |e_2|.
Duplicates are not eliminated and, as we shall see in \Cref{sec:for}, order is maintained; in short
an expression yields a sequences of values, not a bag, and certainly not a set.

The equations we saw in \Cref{sec:unify} can fail, if the arguments
are not equal, yielding no results.  Thus |3=3| succeeds, returns a single result, namely |3|,
while |3=4| fails, returning no results.  In general, we use ``fail''
and ``returns no results'' synonymously.

What if the choice was not at the top-level of an expression?  For example, what does |(3, (7 choice 5))| mean?
In \versecalc{} it does \emph{not} mean a pair with some kind of multi-value in its second component.
Indeed, as you can see from \Cref{fig:syntax}, this expression is syntactically ill-formed.
We must instead give a name to that choice, and then we can put it in the pair, thus: |def x (x = (7 choice 5); (3,x))|.
This is syntactically legal, but what does it mean?  In \versecalc{} a variable is never bound to a multi-value.
Instead, |x| is successively bound to |7|, and then to |5|, like this:
$$
|def x (x = (7 choice 5); (3,x))| \quad = \quad |(def x (x=7; (3,x))) choice (def x (x=5; (3,x))))|
$$
We duplicate the context surrounding the choice, and ``float the choice outwards''.

\subsection{Mixing choice and unification} \label{sec:mixing}

We saw in \Cref{sec:unify} that \emph{equations} are insensitive to sequencing ---
but \emph{choice} is not.
Consider
|def (x,y) (x = (3 choice 4); y = (20 choice 30); (x,y))|.  The choices are made \emph{left-to-right}, so that the result is
|((3,20) choice (3,30) choice (4,20) choice (4,30))|.

So much for choice under unification.  What if we have
unification under choice?  For exapmle:
$$
|def x ((x=3; x+1) choice (x=4; x*2))|
$$
Intuitively, either unify |x| with |3| and return |x+1|, or unify |x| with |4| and return |x*2|.
But so far we have said only ``a program executes by solving its equations'' (\Cref{sec:unify}).
Well, we can see two equations here, |(x=3)| and |(x=4)|, which are mutually contradictory,
so clearly we need to refine our notion of ``solving''.
The answer is pretty clear: in a branch of a choice, solve the equations in that branch
to get the value for some logical variables; and propagate those values to occurrences in
that branch (only). Occurrences of that variable outside the choice are unaffected.

This local-propagation rule would allow us to reason thus:
$$
|def x ((x=3; x+1) choice (x=4; x*2))| \movesto  |def x ((x=3; 4) choice (x=4; 8))|
$$
Are we stuck now?  No, we can float the choice out as
before\footnote{Indeed we could have done so first, had we wished.}, thus
$$
|def x ((x=3; 4) choice (x=4; 8))| \movesto |(def x (x=3; 4)) choice (def x (x=4; 8))| 
$$
and now it is apparent that the sole occurrence of |x| in each |defKW| is the equation
|(x=3)|, or |(x=4)| respectively; so we can drop the |defKW| and the equation, yielding |(4 choice 8)|.
% To take a celebrated example, suppose
% |square = lam x (x*x)|.  What does |applyx square (3 choice 4)| mean? If we make the choice \emph{before}
% the call, the call will yield |9 choice 16|.  But if we a more call-by-name semantics, we might imagine
% it yields |(3 choice 4) * (3 choice 4)| which in turn yields |(9 choice 12 choice 12 choice 16)|.
