\subsection{Pattern matching}

Choice allows us to do pattern matching.  Here is the obligatory append function, where we use the empty tuple |()| to represent the empty list and pairs to represent |Cons|:
\footnote{
Here we allow ourselves to write |lam (x,y) body| rather than |lam p (def (x,y) (p = (x,y); body)|
  }:
$$
|append =lamhdr (xs,ys)| \begin{array}[t]{l}
  |(xs = (); ys) choice| \\
  |(def (x,xs') (xs = (x,xs'); (x, applyx append (xs', ys))))|
\end{array}
$$
If |xs| is |()|, the left hand choice succeeds, returning |y|; and the right hand choice
fails (by attempting to unify |()| with |(x,xs')|).
If |xs| is of form |(y,ys)|,
the right hand choice succeeds, and we make a recursive call to |append|.
Finally if |xs| is built with head normal forms other than the empty tuple and pairs, both choices fail, and |append| returns no
results.

This approach to pattern matching is akin to \emph{narrowing} \cite{hanus:survey}.
Suppose |single = (1, ())|, a singleton list whose only element is 1.
Consider this call:
$$
|def xs (applyx append( xs, single) = single; xs)|
$$
The call to |append| expands into a choice
$$
  |(xs = (); single)| \quad |choice| \quad
  |(def (x,xs') (xs = (x,xs'); (x, applyx append (xs', single))))|
$$
which amounts to exploring the possiblity that |xs| is headed by |()| or a pair -- the
essence of narrowing.  It should not take long to reassure yourself that the program
evaluates to |()|, effectively running |append| backwards in the classic logic-programming manner.

\subsection{Conditionals and |oneKW|} \label{sec:rigid} \label{sec:one}

Every source language will provide a conditional, like |if (x=0) then
e_1 else e_2|.  But what is the equality operator in |(x=0)|?  One
possiblity, adopted by Curry, is this: there is one ``='' for
equations (as in \Cref{sec:unify}), and another, say ``=='', for
testing equality (returning a boolean with constructors |True| and |False|).  \versecalc{} takes a
different, more minimalist position. In \versecalc{} \emph{there is just one equality operator}, written ``='' just as in
\Cref{sec:unify}. The expression |if (x=0) then e_1 else e_2| tries to unify |x| with |0|.  If that succeeds (returns one or more values)
the |if| returns |e_1|; otherwise it returns |e_2|.  There are no data constructors |True| and |False|; instead
failure plays the role of falsity.

But something is terribly wrong here.  Consider |def (x,y) (y = (if (x=0) 3 4); x=7)|.  Presumably this is meant
to set |x| to |7|, test if it is equal to |0| (it is not), and unify |y| with 4.
But what is to stop us instead unifying |x| with |0| (via |(x=0)|), unifying |y| with |3|, and then
failing when we try to unify |x| with |7|?  Not only is that not what we intended, but it also looks very
non-deterministic: the result is affected by the order in which we did unifications!

To address this, we give |if| a special property: unifications inside |e_1| (the condition of the |if|)
can only unify variables |defKW|'d inside |e_1|; varaibles bound outside |e_1| are ``rigid''.  So in our example, the |x| in |(x=0)| is
rigid and cannot be unified.  Instead the |if| is stuck, and we move on to unify |x=7|.  That unblocks
the |if| and all is well.  This special property is precisely the same as the one we sketched for
choice (\Cref{sec:mixing}), where we wanted local equation-solving.

In fact, \versecalc{} distils the three-argument |if| into something simpler, the unary construct |one(e)|.
Its specification is this:
if |e| fails, |one(e)| fails; otherwise |one(e)| returns the first of the values yielded by |e|.
Now, |if e_1 then e_2 else e_3| can (nearly) be re-expressed like this:
$$
|one( (e_1; e_2) choice e_3 )|
$$
If |e_1| fails, the first branch of the choice fails, so we get |e_3|; if |e_1| succeeds, we
get |e_2|, and the outer |oneKW| will select it from the choice.  But this isn't right:
what if |e_2| or |e_3| themselves fail or return multiple results?  Here is a better translation,
which wraps the then and else branches in a thunk:
$$
|applyx (one( (e_1; (lam x e_2)) choice (lam x e_3))) ()|
$$
The argument of |oneKW| evaluates to either |((lam x e_2) choice dots)| or |(lam x e_3)|
depending on whether |e_1| succeeds or fails, respectively, and |oneKW| then picks that lambda and applies it to |()|.
As a bonus, provided we do no evaluation under a lambda, then |e_2| and |e_3| will
remain un-evaluated until the choice is made, just as we expect.

Now |if| is just syntactic sugar, and the special property of |if| becomes a special property of |oneKW|.


\subsection{Arrays and |allKW|} \label{sec:for}
The main data structure in our (reduced) Verse is the array.
An array is a finite sequence of values.
It behaves like a function; indexing is by function application
with the argument being numbers from 0 and up.  Indexing out of range is |fail|.
So, e.g., |def a (a = (10,20,30); applyx a 1)| reduces to |20|.

To go from a multi-valued expression to an array of values there is a |for| construct.
An expression |for^(e_1) in e_2| will evaluate |e_2| for each of the choices in |e_1|.
The |e_1| is called the {\em domain} of the loop.
The scoping is peculiar that variables bound in |e_1| also scope over |e_2|.
So, e.g., |for^(def x (x = 2 `choice` 3 `choice` 5)) in (x+1)| will reduce to the array |(3,4,6)|.
This example can, with the |:=| shorthand, be written |for^(x := 2 `choice` 3 `choice` 5) in (x+1)|.

The |for| construct is akin to list comprehension in languages like Haskell or Python.
Like list comprehension it supports filtering, but in Verse this falls out naturally by just using
a possibly failing expression in the domain.
So, |for^(x := 2 `choice` 3 `choice` 5; x > 2) in (x+1)| reduces to the array |(4,6)|.

Nested iteration in a |for| works as expected, and requires nothing special.
So, |for^(x:=10 `choice` 20; y := 1 `choice` 2 `choice` 3) in x+y| reduces to |(11, 12, 13, 21, 22, 23)|

Just like |if| is defined in terms of the simpler primitive |oneKW| the |for| loop is
defined in terms of the simpler unary |all e|, which simply collects all choices into an array.
It's specification is: if |e| fails the |all e| is the empty array,
otherwise if |e| reduces to |v_1 `choice` dots `choice` v_n| then |all e| is
the array |(v_1, dots, v_n)|.

And just like with |if| we have to be careful when |e_2| itself fails or produces multiple results; simply writing |all (e1;e2)| would give the wrong semantics. So again we put |e_2| under a lambda, and apply each element of the array to |()| afterwards, using the |map| operation. The full desugaring for |for^(e_1) in e_2| is thus
\[
|def y (y = all (e_1; lam x e_2); applyx map ((lam z (applyx z ())), y)|.
\]
We chose to make |map| a built-in operation, but it is not really special: Had we introduced the usual head, tail and cons operations instead we could define |map| with them.

Note how this achieves that peculiar scoping rule: variables defined in |e_1| are in scope in |e_2|.
Any effects (like being multivalued) in |e_2| will not affect the choices defined by |e_1| since they are in a thunk.
So, e.g., |for^(x:=1 `choice` 2) in {3 `choice` x}| will reduce to |(3, 3) `choice` (1, 3) `choice` (3, 2) `choice` (1, 2)|.

The reduction rule for indexing in arrays allows a multi-valued index expression.
For instance, |a := (10,20,30); applyx a (1 `choice` 0 `choice` 1)| will reduce to |20 `choice` 10 `choice` 20|.
It even allows the index to be a logical variable; |def i (applyx a i)| (|a| as as before) reduces to |10 `choice` 20 `choice` 30|.
This is useful since it allows iterating over array elements using |for|.
E.g., |for^(def (i, x) (x = applyx a i)) in x+1| will produce an array with 1 added to the elements of |a|.
And |for^(def (i, x) (x = applyx a i); i > 0) in x| will take the tail of the array |a|.

